This Software does not ship with the full text of the AGPL-3.0 license. To view
the complete AGPL-3.0 terms, please visit the link above.

### 2.2 Applicability

Users who choose the Open Source Edition, provided they comply with all terms
of AGPL-3.0, are entitled to the following rights:

  (a) Completely free for personal use, academic research, and non-commercial
      purposes;
  (b) Freedom to view, copy, modify, and distribute the source code of the
      Software (modified source code must be open-sourced under the same
      license);
  (c) Permission to deploy and run the Software in non-commercial environments.

### 2.3 Key Points of AGPL-3.0

The following is a summary of the core provisions of AGPL-3.0 for reference
only. Please refer to the full legal text at https://www.gnu.org/licenses/
agpl-3.0.html for the complete terms:

  (1) Source Code Disclosure Obligation (Section 13): If you modify the
      Software and provide services to the public over a network (including
      SaaS deployment), you must provide the complete modified source code to
      all users of the service. This means that even if you do not distribute
      copies, merely offering network-based services triggers the source
      code disclosure obligation. This is the core difference between
      AGPL-3.0 and GPL-3.0.

  (2) Copyleft Propagation (Section 5): Any modifications and derivative
      works based on the Software must be released under the same license
      (AGPL-3.0). You may not release modified works based on the Software
      under any other license (including more permissive ones).

  (3) Patent Grant and Termination (Section 11): Each contributor
      automatically grants users a patent license for the contributed code.
      However, if any user initiates patent litigation against any
      contributor, all patent licenses granted under this License to that
      user shall terminate immediately.

  (4) Disclaimer of Warranty (Sections 15, 16): The Software is provided
      "as is" without warranty of any kind. The Author shall not be liable
      for any damages arising from the use of the Software.

  (5) Retention of Copyright and License Notices (Sections 4, 5): All copies
      and modified versions must retain the original copyright notice and
      license notice. The authorship attribution "Jay-Victor" must be
      preserved and shall not be removed or altered.

  (6) Sublicensing Prohibited (Section 10): You may not sublicense the
      Software or its derivative works.

### 2.4 Rights and Obligations of Open Source Edition Users

【What You CAN Do】:
  ✓ Use the Software for personal study and research purposes.
  ✓ View and modify the source code for non-commercial purposes.
  ✓ Use the Software in non-commercial projects, subject to AGPL-3.0 terms.
  ✓ Contribute code modifications and improvements to the community.

【What You MUST Do】:
  ✦ Retain the authorship attribution "Jay-Victor" and all copyright notices.
  ✦ If you modify the Software and provide network-based services, you must
    disclose the complete modified source code.
  ✦ Any derivative works must be released under the same license (AGPL-3.0).
  ✦ Include this License and the AGPL-3.0 license (or a link to it) with
    any distribution.

【What You MUST NOT Do】:
  ✗ Use the Software or its derivatives for commercial purposes without a
    commercial license.
  ✗ Remove or alter the original copyright notices and authorship attribution.
  ✗ Release modified works based on the Software under a non-AGPL-3.0 license
    (sublicensing).
  ✗ Mix AGPL-3.0 code with closed-source commercial code in an attempt to
    circumvent the open source obligations.
